2.3. Quality assessment
To assess the quality of each selected study, a 10-point checklist 
involved in previous neuroimaging meta-analyses was used (Supple-
mentary Materials, Table S1) (Gong et al., 2020a; Shepherd et al., 2012). 
C.C., G.Z.X., and S.S.L. independently conducted the literature search, 
study evaluation, and selection. Any discrepancies were resolved by W. 
Y., the nal investigator. This study was conducted according to the 
Meta-analysis of Observational Studies in Epidemiology (MOOSE) 
guideline for meta-analyses of observational studies (Stroup et al., 
2000).
2.4. Data extraction
Among the included studies, demographic and clinical characteris-
tics (sex, sample size, age, IQ, education duration, IQ) were collected. An 
analysis methodology includes the imaging parameters, full width at 
half maximum (FWHM) of the main ndings, software packages, and a 
method to correct for multiple comparisons, as well as the statistical 
threshold of the main ndings. Using the data from original studies, we 
extracted the peak coordinates that protrude the difference between 
