2.5. Data analysis
2.5.1. Voxel-based meta-analysis for functional differences
A meta-analysis was conducted to compare resting-state functional 
activity differences between ADHD and NCs (i.e., ALFF, fALFF and 
ReHo) using the (Seed-based 
Mapping) SDM software package, 
d 
following a standardized procedure available at (www.sdmproject. 
com). In the SDM method, reported peak coordinates from original 
studies are amalgamated with statistical parametric maps, and brain 
maps illustrating the effect size of contrast results are reconstructed. The 
analysis adhered to the SDM tutorials and previous publications (Gao 
et al., 2018; Gong et al., 2020b; Yan et al., 2023; Yang et al., 2023b), and 
the results obtained from SDM were visualized using MRIcron (www. 
mricro.com/mricron/).
The SDM approach is succinctly detailed herein. Firstly, we extracted 
peak coordinates 165and effect sizes (e.g., -values) that denote differ-
t
ences in ALFF/fALFF/ReHo between ADHD and NCs from each dataset. 
Secondly, Coordinates initially reported in Talairach space are auto-
matically transformed to MNI space within the SDM software through 
matrix transformation, ensuring spatial consistency in the comparison 
(Lancaster et al., 2007 Radua and Mataix-Cols, 2009
; 
). Following this, a 
standard MNI map illustrating functional differences was independently 
reconstructed for each database using an anisotropic Gaussian kernel. 
Finally, the mean map was generated through voxel-wise calculation of 
the random-effects mean of the dataset maps, with weighting based on 
sample size, intra-dataset variance, and between-dataset heterogeneity 
(
). Meta-analyses were conducted using the default 
Radua et al., 2012b
SDM kernel size and threshold (FWHM = 20 mm, uncorrected p < 0.005 
with peak Z > 1 and a cluster extent of 50 voxels), in accordance with the 
recommendations of the SDM software developer (
; 
Müller et al., 2018
Radua et al., 2012b). These parameters have been validated to effec-
tively balance false positives and negatives, providing an approximation 
to corrected results (
; 
Lieberman and Cunningham, 2009 Müller et al., 
2018; Radua et al., 2012b). It is important to note that this FWHM kernel 
is designed to assign proximity indicators to reported coordinates and 
not to smooth different images. The results were presented in MNI 
coordinates.
