2.7. Jackknife sensitivity analysis
We conducted a jackknife sensitivity analysis at the whole-brain 
voxel level to evaluate reproducibility. This process involved itera-
tively repeating the same analyses while excluding one dataset at a time 
(Radua et al., 2014). If a brain region remained signicant in all or most 
combinations of analyses, it was considered highly replicable.
2.8. Analysis of heterogeneity and publication bias
The analysis of residual heterogeneity, assessed through the I2 sta-
tistic in the included studies, was conducted to assess result robustness, 
with an I2 value below 50 % typically indicating low heterogeneity 
(Egger et al., 1997). To explore potential publication bias quantitatively, 
Egger s test was employed, and funnel plots were generated (
’
Sterne 
et al., 2011). A result with 
0.05 was considered statistically signif-
p <
icant for publication bias.
2.9. Meta-regression analyses
The potential impacts of relevant demographic and clinical variables 
(age, percentage of males, education duration, and IQ) on regional brain 
functional and structural alterations in individuals with ADHD were 
examined using a random-effects general linear meta-regression. In 
accordance with the recommendations of the SDM methods developer 
(
) and previous meta-analyses (
; 
Radua et al., 2012b
Radua et al., 2012a
Su et al., 2021), a more conservative threshold of p < 0.005 was selected 
to minimize false positives. We excluded ndings in brain regions other 
than those identied in the main meta-analyses (
).
