3.5. Subgroup analysis
3.5.1. Resting-state functional imaging analysis
In children subgroup (24 datasets), the results were consistent with 
the main functional results. In drug naïve subgroup (22 datasets), in-
dividuals with ADHD displayed increased functional activity in the 
bilateral OFC, and decreased functional activity in the bilateral PCC 
extending to bilateral precuneus, and bilateral MCC extending to the 
bilateral ACC/ mPFC (Table S6 and Fig. S2). Additionally, in the results 
for the subgroups of ALFF (14 datasets), we found that increased ALFF in 
the bilateral OFC (extending to the bilateral ACC), left cerebellum, and 
left caudate nucleus, and decreased ALFF in the bilateral ACC/ mPFC 
extending to MCC, left precentral gyrus (extending to the left IFG), and 
bilateral inferior parietal gyri (IPG). Meanwhile, individuals with ADHD 
also revealed that in increased ReHo (10 datasets) in the right para-
hippocampal gyrus (extending to the right fusiform gyrus and right 
cerebellum), left OFC (extending to the left striatum), and decreased 
ReHo in the right insula (extending to the right STG) (see Table S5 and 
Fig. S1, S2). There were not sufcient studies of the adult subgroup (0 
datasets), fALFF subgroup (2 datasets), and ReHo subgroup (5 datasets) 
to conduct subgroup meta-analysis.
3.5.2. VBM imaging analysis
The study participants were divided into two distinct subgroups: 
adult and pediatric individuals (encompassing both adolescents and 
children). In the subgroup analyses focusing on VBM, we noted that, in 
comparison to NCs, a subgroup of pediatric individuals with ADHD 
(involving 39 datasets) exhibited decreased GMV in the right caudate 
nucleus (extending to the bilateral ACC and right OFC), bilateral OFC, 
bilateral ACC/ mPFC, right STG, left precentral gyrus, and left IFG 
(extending to the left insula) (see Table S6 and Fig. S1 for detailed in-
formation in Supplementary Materials). In subgroups of adult in-
dividuals with ADHD (consisting of 11 studies), we observed decreased 
GMV in the right STG (extending to the right middle temporal gyrus), 
and bilateral striatum (extending to the right OFC) (Table S6 and 
Fig. S1). In drug naïve subgroup (36 datasets), individuals with ADHD 
exhibited decreased GMV in the right STG extending to right insula and 
MTG, bilateral OFC (extending to the bilateral ACC), right SFG, left IFG, 
left precentral gyrus (extending to the left postcentral gyrus), and right 
gyrus rectus (Table S6 and Fig. S2).
