## Methodology
Methods: A comprehensive voxel-wise meta-analysis was performed on studies employing resting-state functional 
imaging and gray matter volume (GMV), examining discrepancies between individuals with ADHD and neuro-
typical controls (NCs). The analysis utilized the Seed-based 
Mapping software.
d 
Results: A systematic review of the literature identied 21 functional imaging studies (595 ADHD and 564 
controls) and 50 GMV studies (1907 ADHD and 1611 controls). In general, individuals with ADHD exhibited 
increased resting-state functional activity in the right parahippocampal gyrus and bilateral orbitofrontal cortex 
(OFC), as well as decreased resting-state functional activity in the bilateral cingulate cortex (including the 
posterior cingulate cortex [PCC], median cingulate cortex [MCC], and anterior cingulate cortex [ACC]). The VBM 
meta-analysis revealed decreased GMV in the bilateral OFC, right putamen (extending to right superior temporal 
gyrus [STG]), left inferior frontal gyrus (IFG), right superior frontal gyrus (SFG), ACC, and precentral gyrus 
among individuals with ADHD.

## Results
results have been inconsistent.

## Clinical Significance
Conclusions: The multimodal meta-analyses indicated that individuals with ADHD exhibit abnormalities in both 
function and structure in the bilateral OFC. In addition, a few regions exhibited only functional or only structural 
abnormalities in ADHD, such as in the limbic, prefrontal, primary sensorimotor regions.
1. Introduction
Attention-decit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) is a severe neuro-
developmental disorder characterized by age-inappropriate symptoms 
of inattention and hyperactivity (
). Early clinical in-
Lukito et al., 2020
vestigations revealed that over 5 % of children and adolescents world-
wide are affected by ADHD (
). Certain symptoms 
Polanczyk et al., 2014
shown by children with ADHD may persist into adulthood (Sibley et al., 
2017), which can impact various aspects of their life, or physical and 
psychological well-being (including causing them to have destructive 
behaviors, anxiety, depression, and substance use disorders)(Biederman 
et al., 1993; McGough et al., 2005). ADHD has resulted in worse clinical 
manifestations and a poor prognosis, causing substantial impacts on 
public health (
). Despite recent insights from da 
Asherson et al., 2012
Silva BS et al. and Faraone SV et al. on the importance of genetic, 
epigenetic, and environmental factors in ADHD, further investigation 
into its pathophysiology and neuroanatomical mechanisms is essential 
(
; 
).
da Silva et al., 2023 Faraone et al., 2024
In ADHD, it is theorized that brain abnormalities suggest delayed 
maturation in brain structure and function, resulting in late-developing 
cognitive functions (
; 
; 
Hoogman et al., 2017 Lukito et al., 2020 Shaw 
et al., 2007 Sripada et al., 2014
; 
). Compared with task-based fMRI, 
resting-state functional MRI (rs-fMRI) does not depend on external tasks 
or stimuli and can better predict individual differences in neural activity 
to a certain extent (Lem´ee et al., 2019 Tavor et al., 2016
; 
). Among the 
various rs-fMRI analytic methods, the use of amplitude of low-frequency 
uctuations (ALFF)/fractional ALFF (fALFF) and regional homogeneity 
(ReHo) are primary approaches for characterizing regional spontaneous 
