activity signals at the single-voxel level from different perspectives (Y. 
Zang et al., 2004; Y. F. Zang et al., 2007 Zou et al., 2008
; 
). ALFF/fALFF 
results correlate with local eld potential activity, indicating the 
strength of low-frequency oscillations (Biswal et al., 1997; Cordes et al., 
2001). ReHo signies the functional similarity and synchronization 
between the time series of a specic voxel and its nearest neighbors (Y. 
Zang et al., 2004). Meta-analyses employing a combined strategy have 
delineated regional brain dysfunction in clinical populations with bi-
polar disorder, major depressive disorder, and social anxiety disorder 
(
; 
; 
; Y. 
Chen et al., 2022 Diener et al., 2012 Gray et al., 2020
Li et al., 
2016). From a neuropathological viewpoint, uctuations in ALFF/fALFF 
or ReHo in the brains of individuals with ADHD could indicate neural 
activity. Several studies using ALFF/fALFF or ReHo have shown altered 
functional activity in various brain regions, including the OFC (F. Li 
et al., 2014
Li et al., 2014
), superior frontal gyrus (SFG)(F. 
), medial 
prefrontal cortex (Jiang et al., 2020), and cingulate cortex in individuals 
with ADHD (An et al., 2013). These results diverged, potentially because 
of the diverse clinical heterogeneity (including sex, age range, period-
icity of disorder, primary diagnosis of disorder, and drug status), limited 
sample sizes, and methodology. Hence, a meta-analysis that consoli-
dates ndings from various studies is necessary for a comprehensive and 
robust understanding of the literature. However, there is no meta- 
analysis of spontaneous neural activity via rs-fMRI in ADHD individuals.
In addition to alterations in functional activity, differences in struc-
tural markers, such as gray matter volume (GMV), are crucial, as they 
may be relatively stable and serve as a foundation for functional neural 
activity (
). Voxel-based morphometrics (VBM) is an 
Qi et al., 2022
automatic voxel-wise method used to investigate GMV differences in an 
unbiased manner (
). Differences in structural markers 
Nemoto, 2017
may underlie functional neural activity, and a multimodal meta-analysis 
could provide a more comprehensive approach to explore the associa-
tion between structure and function (
). A recent 
Yang et al., 2023a
structural meta-analysis of individuals with ADHD (1533 individuals 
with ADHD and 1295 controls) reported decreased GMV in the OFC in 
individuals with ADHD (
). Another structural meta- 
Lukito et al., 2020
analysis (1211 individuals with ADHD and 1032 controls) demon-
strated decreased GMV in the limbic system (Yu et al., 2022). Long et al. 
conducted a meta-analysis on 619 individuals with ADHD and 483 
controls and revealed decreased GMV in the prefrontal cortex and pre-
central gyrus (Long et al., 2022). However, The inconsistent ndings of 
recent meta-analyses may be ascribed to several factors, including a 
limited number of studies, varying inclusion and exclusion criteria, 
overly permissive statistical thresholds, heterogeneity in hypotheses and 
clinical populations, methodological discrepancies, and diverse prac-
tices regarding the disclosure of negative study outcomes (Müller et al., 
2018; Tahmasian et al., 2018a, 2018b). To address these challenges, we 
performed a detailed meta-analysis using the largest ADHD study 
collection, aiming to identify consistent brain abnormalities in ADHD 
individuals versus neurotypical controls. By integrating relevant studies, 
we offered a comprehensive view of gray matter and functional issues 
associated with ADHD (Radua et al., 2012a Raschle et al., 2015
; 
; Sacher 
et al., 2012 Tahmasian et al., 2018a, 2018b Zakzanis et al., 2003
; 
; 
). 
Subgroup analyses were also conducted to account for heterogeneity, 
considering ADHD subtype, medication status, and age.
Based on existing studies, we hypothesized that functional and 
structural alterations were found in the OFC, insula, cingulate cortex, 
prefrontal lobe and limbic systems in individuals with ADHD compared 
those in NCs, and that there was an overlap of functional and GMV 
changes. The ndings of this meta-analysis could provide an approach 
for further research, adding to a deeper comprehensive understanding of 
the pathophysiology and neuroanatomical mechanism of ADHD.
